%U A394415 26,26,27,28,29,30,31,32,32,32,33,34,35,35,35,35,35,35,35
%N A394415 On a graph with points (k, prime(k)), k>=1, consider if prime(n) is on any previously drawn infinite line between prime(j) and prime(j-1), where 2<=j<=n-1. If not, add one to the count of primes not on any such line, and then, regardless of if prime(n) is on a line, draw an infinite line between prime(n) and prime(n-1). The sequence gives the total number of primes not on any previously drawn infinite line, starting from prime(2).
%C A394415 The sequence overall shows long periods of near linear growth interrupted by short periods of much slower growth, with the later periods getting further apart as n increases. See the attaching images.
%C A394415 In the first 1000000 terms the longest run of equal terms is 536 terms all equal to 7161, from a(16996) to a(17531). This run is eventually broken by prime(17532) = 194483. There is no other run of equal terms approaching this length in the first 1000000 terms, and given this occurs after only 16996 terms, it is plausible this is the longest run of equal terms for all n, although this is unknown.
%C A394415 See A394420 for the primes that are not on any previously drawn line.
%H A394415 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A394415/b394415.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..10000</a>
%H A394415 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A394415/a394415.png">Image of the first 20000 terms</a>. The run of terms a(16996)..a(17531) = 7161 is highlighted in red. The green line is a(n) = n.
%H A394415 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A394415/a394415_1.png">Image of the first 1000000 terms</a>.
%e A394415 a(3) = 2 as the point (3,prime(3)) = (3,5) is not on the one previously drawn line between (2,prime(2)) = (2,3) and (1,prime(1)) = (1,2).
%e A394415 a(4) = 2 as the point (4, prime(4)) = (4,7) is on the previously drawn line between prime(3) = 5 and prime(2) = 3.
%e A394415 a(10) = 7 as the point (10,prime(10)) = (10,29) is on the line drawn between prime(7) = 17 and prime(6) = 13. This is the second of fifteen consecutive terms equal to 7.
%e A394415 a(25) = 8 as the point (25,prime(25)) = (25,97) is on the line drawn between prime(22) = 79 and prime(21) = 73. This is the first term to differ from A394972.
%Y A394415 Cf. A394420 (primes not on any previous line), A394972, A000040, A373813, A376187.
%K A394415 nonn,new
